## My thinking, phase by phase

### Phase 1 — Data Cleaning & EDA
Before touching any model, I spent real time just looking at the data —
duplicate invoices, negative quantities (returns), missing customer IDs,
inconsistent country names. My rule for myself here: **don't engineer a
feature on data you haven't visually checked.** Two EDA passes
(`eda3.ipynb` + a second cleaning pass) later, I had a `clean_sales.csv`
I trusted enough to build on.

### Phase 2 — Feature Engineering
I split features into four families instead of dumping everything into one
notebook, because each family has a different grain (per-transaction,
per-customer, per-product, per-country):

```
Raw Sales
   │
   ▼
Time Features        (day of week, month, seasonality)
   │
   ▼
Customer Features    (recency, frequency, monetary value)
   │
   ▼
Product Features     (velocity, revenue share)
   │
   ▼
Country Features     (regional demand patterns)
   │
   ▼
ML-ready Dataset
```

### Phase 3 — Customer Intelligence & Churn
Using the RFM (Recency, Frequency, Monetary) features from Phase 2, I built
a `customer_360.csv` profile per customer, ran segmentation to group
customers by value, and layered a churn model on top to flag customers
whose behavior is drifting away from their segment's norm.

### Phase 4 — Demand Forecasting
This is the module I iterated on the most — `feature_builder` →
`train_model` → `evaluate` as three separate notebooks so I could swap
models without re-deriving features every time. Metrics are logged to
`src/outputs/forecasting/metrics/model_metrics.csv` so the dashboard's
Model Performance page always reflects the latest trained model, not a
hardcoded number.

### Phase 5 — Inventory Optimization
I used **ABC analysis** to classify products by revenue contribution:

```
A Items → Top 80% of revenue
B Items → Next 15% of revenue
C Items → Last 5% of revenue
```

paired with **XYZ analysis** (demand variability) so a product isn't just
ranked by how much money it makes, but also by how *predictable* it is —
which directly drives safety stock and reorder point calculations, and
ultimately a stockout risk score per product:

```
Sales Data → Product Statistics → ABC Analysis → XYZ Analysis
   → Safety Stock → Reorder Point → Stockout Risk → Inventory Dashboard
```

### Phase 6 — Recommendation Engine
The module I wanted to prove I could go beyond "just analytics." I
implemented **Market Basket Analysis using the Apriori algorithm** to mine
association rules from real transaction baskets:

```
Customer Transactions → Transaction Matrix → Apriori Algorithm
   → Association Rules → Frequently Bought Together → Recommendation Engine
```

### Phase 7 — Dashboard (tying it together)
Everything above is not much use to a business user if it stays in a
notebook. `app.py` is a multi-page Streamlit app where each page maps to a
module:

- `1_Executive_Overview.py` — headline KPIs
- `2_Sales_Analytics.py` — revenue/time trends
- `3_Customer_Intelligence.py` — segments & customer 360
- `4_Demand_Forecasting.py` — forecast vs actuals
- `5_Inventory_Optimization.py` — ABC/XYZ, stockout risk
- `6_Recommendation_Engine.py` — association rules
- `7_Model_Performance.py` — model metrics, so the numbers are auditable

